June 8, 2018:''' Arkansas wide receiver Kofi Boateng announced his retirement from football following two knee injuries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://247sports.com/college/arkansas/Article/Kofi-Boateng-walking-away-from-Arkansas-Razorbacks-football-following-knee-injuries-ACL-wide-receiver-118897142 |title=Kofi Boateng walking away from football after knee injuries |last=Biddy |first=Trey |date=June 8, 2018 |website=247sports.com |publisher=24/7 Sports |access-date=June 8, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''July 10, 2018:''' The Arkansas athletic department released the design of the 2018 uniform, which featured small tweaks from the past few years. These changes included the elimination of matte-finish helmets in favor of a glossier \"pearl cardinal\" finish, removal of details on the jersey to \"de-clutter\" the chest area, and a new stripe design on the pants.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/modern-style-traditional-fire/ |title=Modern Style + Traditional \ud83d\udd25 |last=McGillis |first=Trevor |date=July 10, 2018 |website=arkansasrazorbacks.com |publisher=University of Arkansas |access-date=July 17, 2018}}\n</ref>\n*'''July 20, 2018:''' The SEC media poll was released, and placed the Razorbacks last out of the seven teams in the SEC West. The Hogs received 412 votes, 166 shy of sixth-place Ole Miss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/sec/2018/07/20/alabama-georgia-dominate-preseason-sec-college-football-media-poll/807832002/ |title=Alabama, Georgia dominate preseason SEC college football media poll |date=July 20, 2018 |publisher=USA Today |access-date=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''July 21, 2018:''' The Razorbacks had three players selected to the preseason all-SEC teams. The second-team offense featured OL Hjalte Froholdt, and the third-team defense featured LB De'Jon Harris and DB Santos Ramirez.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.secsports.com/article/24148392/media-predicts-alabama-win-2018-sec-championship |title=Media predicts Alabama to win 2018 SEC Championship |date=July 21, 2018 |website=secsports.com |publisher=Southeastern Conference |access-date=July 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Award watch lists===\n<small>Listed in the order that they were released</small>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Arkansas Razorbacks|Award|Player|Position|Year}}\n|-\n|[[Chuck Bednarik Award]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Bednarik Award Watch List|url=https://www.maxwellfootballclub.org/2018-maxwell-bednarik-watch-list|date=July 16, 2018|accessdate=July 16, 2018}}</ref>\n|De'Jon Harris\n|Linebacker\n|Junior\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Doak Walker Award]]<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 Doak Walker Award Candidates|url=https://www.smu.edu/DoakWalkerAward/Candidates|date=July 18, 2018|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|Chase Hayden\n|Running back\n|Sophomore\n|-\n|Devwah Whaley\n|Running back\n|Junior\n|-\n|rowspan=2|[[Butkus Award]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebutkusaward.com/watchlist/view.aspx?t=c |title=Butkus Award - 2018 Collegiate Watchlist |date=July 23, 2018 |publisher=The Butkus Award |access-date=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Dre Greenlaw]]\n|Linebacker\n|Senior\n|-\n|De'Jon Harris\n|Linebacker\n|Junior\n|-\n|[[Bronko Nagurski Trophy]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Langlois |first1=Brandon |title=Harris Adds Another Honor |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/harris-adds-another-honor/ |website=arkansasrazorbacks.com |publisher=University of Arkansas |accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|De'Jon Harris\n|Linebacker\n|Junior\n|-\n|[[Outland Trophy]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Langlois |first1=Brandon |title=Froholdt On Outland Trophy Watch List |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/froholdt-on-outland-trophy-watch-list/ |website=arkansasrazorbacks.com |publisher=University of Arkansas |accessdate=July 24, 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Hjalte Froholdt]]\n|Offensive lineman\n|Senior\n|-\n|[[Wuerffel Trophy]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Wuerffel Trophy Unveils 2018 Watch List|url=https://www.wuerffeltrophy.org/news1/wuerffel-trophy-unveils-2018-watch-list|date=July 26, 2018|accessdate=July 26, 2018}}</ref>\n|Hjalte Froholdt\n|Offensive lineman\n|Senior\n|}\n\n===Spring game===\nThe 2018 Arkansas Red\u2013White Spring Football Game took place at War Memorial Stadium in [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]], with kickoff at 1:00&nbsp;p.m. CT on April 7.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/2018-red-white-game-headed-to-little-rock/ |title=2018 Red-White Game Headed to Little Rock |last=Langlois |first=Brandon |date=January 25, 2018 |website=arkansasrazorbacks.com |publisher=University of Arkansas |access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seccountry.com/arkansas/arkansas-play-2018-spring-football-game-little-rock |title=Arkansas to play 2018 spring football game in Little Rock |last=Shadid |first=Trent |date=February 2018 |website=seccountry.com |publisher=SEC Country |access-date=April 6, 2018}}</ref> It was broadcast on the [[SEC Network]].<ref name= \"schedule\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fbschedules.com/ncaa-18/2018-arkansas-razorbacks-football-schedule.php |title=2018 Arkansas Razorbacks football schedule |website=fbschedules.com |publisher=FB Schedules |access-date=April 6, 2018}}</ref> The white team consisted of the offense and the red team consisted of the defense.\n\nThe spring game followed a different format: the game was played in twelve minute quarters, rather than fifteen, with a running clock in the second half. The game was scored traditionally on offense (white team), but the defense (red team) could earn points for a variety of achievements (6 pts. for touchdown, 3 for turnover or 4th down stop, 2 for three-and-out, 2 for blocked kick, 1 for sack or TFL).<ref name= \"spring\">{{cite web |url=http://www.arkansasonline.com/news/2018/apr/07/live-updates-arkansas-spring-game/ |title=Recapping Arkansas' spring game |last=Bordelon |first=Scottie |date=April 7, 2018 |website=arkansasonline.com |publisher=ArkansasOnline |access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n! Date !! Time !! Spring Game !! Site !! TV !! Result !! Attendance !! Source\n|-\n|April 7||1:00&nbsp;p.m.||Red vs. White Spring Game|| [[War Memorial Stadium (Arkansas)|War Memorial Stadium]] \u2022 [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock, AR]] || [[SEC Network|SECN]] || '''White''' 27\u201325 || style=\"text-align:center\"|7,000 || style=text-align:center|<ref name=\"spring\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/stats/football/2018/RedWhiteResults.pdf |title=White vs. Red Results |date=April 7, 2018 |website=arkansasrazorbacks.com |publisher=University of Arkansas |access-date=April 9, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Schedule==\nThe Razorbacks' 2018 schedule consisted of 7 home games, 4 away games, and 1 neutral game in the regular season. The Razorbacks hosted SEC foes [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]], [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]] (in [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]]), [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]], and [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]], and traveled to [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn]], [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]], and [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]]. Arkansas played against [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] in [[Arlington, Texas]] for the [[Arkansas\u2013Texas A&M football rivalry|fifth year in a row]].\n\nArkansas hosted three of its four of its non\u2013conference games: against [[Eastern Illinois Panthers football|Eastern Illinois]] from the [[Ohio Valley Conference]], [[North Texas Mean Green football|North Texas]] from [[Conference USA]], and [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]] from the [[American Athletic Conference]]. The lone away non\u2013conference game saw the Hogs travel to [[Fort Collins, Colorado]] to play [[Colorado State Rams football|Colorado State]], from the [[Mountain West Conference]].\n\nPer southernpigskin.com, the Razorbacks' schedule ranked as the 39th-toughest of the 66 Power Five teams in the nation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southernpigskin.com/sec/2018-strength-of-schedule-rankings/ |title=2018 Strength of Schedule Rankings |last=Smith |first=Matt |website=southernpigskin.com |publisher=Southern Pigskin |access-date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{CFB schedule\n| opprank = y\n| rankyear = 2018\n| rankdivision = NCAA Division I FBS\n| poll = AP\n| timezone = Central\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n|date = September 1\n|time = 3:00 p.m.\n|opponent = [[2018 Eastern Illinois Panthers football team|Eastern Illinois]]<ncg>\n|stadium = [[Donald W. Reynolds Razorback Stadium]]\n|cityst = [[Fayetteville, Arkansas|Fayetteville, AR]]\n|tv = [[SEC Network|SECN]]\n|w/l = w\n|score = 55\u201320\n|attend = 63,342\n|source = <ref name= \"eiu-nt\">{{cite web |url=https://247sports.com/college/arkansas/Article/Game-times-for-Arkansas-Razorbacks-football-2018-Eastern-Illinois-Colorado-State-North-Texas-118668381/ |title=Game times and networks for first three weeks of Hog football |last=Biddy |first=Trey |date=May 31, 2018 |website=247sports.com |publisher=24/7 Sports |access-date=June 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=401012247 |title=Eastern Illinois at Arkansas - Game Summary |website=espn.com |publisher=ESPN |access-date=January 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Eastern Illinois vs Arkansas (Sep 01, 2018) |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/pdf/football/2018/stats/01-EIU.pdf |publisher=University of Arkansas |accessdate=September 11, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n|date = September 8\n|time = 6:30 p.m.\n|away = y\n|opprank = \n|opponent = [[2018 Colorado State Rams football team|Colorado State]]<ncg>\n|stadium = [[Canvas Stadium]]\n|cityst = [[Fort Collins, Colorado|Fort Collins, CO]]\n|tv = [[CBS Sports Network|CBSSN]]\n|w/l = l\n|score = 27\u201334\n|attend = 31,894\n|source = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arkansasrazorbacks.com/colorado-state-kickoff-time-tv-network-announced/ |title=Colorado State K